name: Jeff Is Really Damn Blue
tweet: Now there's nothing out there.  I wonder if old Henry Belcher would recognize his ranch. One of these days we'll go back, and sit on the porch, and drink to the memory of the tough Texans who carved a life out of such a hard land.

name: Jeff Is Really Damn Blue
tweet: Every so often I think about the people who lived in that cabin. The Belcher's ran up to 3,000 head of longhorn cattle. A decade later, the land no longer supported cattle, and the new rancher switched to sheep and goats.

name: Jeff Is Really Damn Blue
tweet: I visited the cabin in 2015 with my camping buddy. It's about an hour drive through the park on a very rough dirt road; you will need a high-clearance 4x4, and you need to unlock a gate with a key you check out at the park ranger station. The photos are all mine. pic.twitter.com/Df5FYDSAVw

name: Jeff Is Really Damn Blue
tweet: Dolf Williams ranched this area until 1941, and after he died in 1942, the ranch was purchased by Judge J.C. Hunter. Judge Hunter's son sold the ranch to the National Park Service in 1966. The park service has maintained the cabin, which is in remarkable shape.

name: Jeff Is Really Damn Blue
tweet: But by 1917, rains had diminished, and that combined with overgrazing had reduced grasses, which were replaced with scrub. The Belcher's departed, and James Adolphus Williams bought the ranch. He ran sheep and goats, which were better suited to the more arid environment.

name: Jeff Is Really Damn Blue
tweet: ...longhorn cattle they ran in this valley and nearby. Again, it was a very different place than now. Game was abundant, as were predators: bear, wolves, lions, bobcats, coyotes. Birds, including migratory birds and songbirds, were abundant. Photo: view from the porch. pic.twitter.com/GE6ywlq8xn

name: Jeff Is Really Damn Blue
tweet: Its difficult to show in these photos how small you feel at this house. Those peaks behind rise 5,000 ft above you as you stand there. It is absolutely silent but for the wind glowing through the scrub. But the Belcher's would have heard the sounds of the couple thousand... pic.twitter.com/LRi02Ambvl

name: Jeff Is Really Damn Blue
tweet: Since his brother and his wife had left, Henry Belcher moved in with his wife Rena and their baby daughter Bernice. The house had a wood stove, bunk beds, and other furniture, and a luxury for the time, wallpaper. Water came from catchment tanks at the base of the mtns. pic.twitter.com/5428IPSVRJ

name: Jeff Is Really Damn Blue
tweet: Here is the house. You can see it in the far distance. Can you imagine, in 1908, riding a horse carriage or wagon or whatever to this place, far off the edge of the middle of nowhere? "Look honey, there's our new house!" pic.twitter.com/ryJnkPsdUy

name: Jeff Is Really Damn Blue
tweet: In 1908, the brother of a man named Henry Belcher had a house built for him and his new bride on the south-west slope of the Guadalupe Mtns. She spent one night in the house and had enough; she left and never returned.

name: Jeff Is Really Damn Blue
tweet: This is a very remote area even today. Now it is desert, but in the 19th and early 20th centuries, the area received more rain than now, and the natural grass was enough to support livestock so there were some isolated ranches. pic.twitter.com/WnPuUcW2AX

name: Jeff Is Really Damn Blue
tweet: This is a view of the Guadalupe Mountains. They are part of a massive fossilized reef that was the shore of the shallow sea that covered most of what is now Texas 300 million years ago. The fossilized reef was uplifted, and became these mountains. pic.twitter.com/1UDrTvgCLW

name: Jeff Is Really Damn Blue

tweet: A couple years later, the INF Treaty banned those intermediate range nuclear forces that had ratcheted up tensions and made the 80s so dangerous. And then of course the Wall came down, the Soviet Union collapsed, and Poland, and other eastern states joined NATO.
